WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:01.320
Great, thank you Max,

00:00:01.320 --> 00:00:03.440
and thank you for attending this session

00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:07.380
and my talk on perfectly parallel, perfectly distributed.

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:09.920
I'm Charlie Gao, I'm a software engineer

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:12.480
on the open source team here at Posit.

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:15.280
And hopefully you're suitably curious

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.120
about one of the two things in the title.

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:20.240
So, in this presentation,

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:22.940
I'm hopefully going to be answering the question,

00:00:23.799 --> 00:00:25.360
why do we have parallel purrr,

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:26.740
and why do we have it now?

00:00:27.799 --> 00:00:29.600
And then distributed purrr,

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:31.760
why might I want to use that?

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:33.919
And if so, how would I go about doing that?

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:38.119
So I'm going to start with this diagram,

00:00:38.119 --> 00:00:40.040
which I borrowed from Hadley Wickham.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:43.680
It's his famous Life Cycle of a Data Scientist.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:47.360
So where does purrr feature in this diagram?

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:50.419
Well, you can find it in the bottom left-hand corner

00:00:50.419 --> 00:00:51.360
in the programming.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:56.439
So it's not used for any particular step in this life cycle,

00:00:56.439 --> 00:00:59.400
but it's used throughout the life cycle

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:03.439
as a means to program more reliably and consistently.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.839
So how has the purrr ecosystem evolved over time?

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:15.800
Well, purrr itself is now 10 years old.

00:01:16.959 --> 00:01:19.720
Purrr has one of the most adorable,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:24.199
most recognizable hex logos in the entire R ecosystem.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:28.080
And it's maintained, of course, by our very own Hadley Wickham.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:33.599
Some of you may have also come across this package.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:37.000
Purrr has been with us for a surprisingly long time,

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.320
since 2018, in fact.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:42.080
And this is a parallel copy of purrr,

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.820
which uses similar syntax to run things in parallel.

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:48.879
This is maintained by Davis Vaughn,

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:51.400
one of my colleagues also in the tidyverse.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:54.239
And he has also been instrumental

00:01:54.239 --> 00:01:56.260
in developing parallel purrr.

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:58.839
So we've taken his years of experience

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:00.320
in maintaining purrr,

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:02.860
and put them into making parallel purrr

00:02:02.860 --> 00:02:04.419
the best that it can be today.

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:10.320
Fast forward to 2022.

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.800
This is the year that I released Mirai.

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:18.559
Mirai is a modern way to do parallel

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:20.320
and async programming in R.

00:02:22.639 --> 00:02:27.639
So if we cross purrr and Mirai to do parallel purrr,

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:33.119
first of all, what would the hex logo look like?

00:02:35.399 --> 00:02:37.240
For those observant amongst you,

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.360
you would have noticed that furr upgrades

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:41.919
the cat of purrr into a lion,

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:43.559
albeit still a very sleepy one.

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:48.160
So if you take Mirai, which is much more high-powered,

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:50.839
and you cross it with purrr, what would you get?

00:02:50.839 --> 00:02:54.559
And this is something that I actually asked Hadley himself

00:02:54.559 --> 00:02:56.240
a couple of weeks ago.

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:59.360
And he actually answered without any hesitation at all.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:02.679
And he said, you would probably get four cats.

00:03:02.679 --> 00:03:07.679
So now you have literally four cats running in parallel.

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:11.320
So jokes on the hex logo aside,

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:15.600
this was born in July 2025, so a couple of months ago.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.279
This is very much the newest,

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:19.360
shiniest thing in the UK system.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:23.880
So to answer the question, why do we have parallel purrr

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:25.399
and why do we have it now?

00:03:26.279 --> 00:03:28.639
The answer is both purrr and Mirai

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:31.559
were designed to be used reliably in programming.

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:35.000
So if you remember back to the first slide,

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:39.440
purrr was used for programming.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.479
And why can I say the same thing about Mirai?

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:46.759
Well, Mirai has this design philosophy.

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:50.440
It's based on four pillars.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:51.839
It has a modern foundation,

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:54.399
which gives it the performance that it has.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:57.039
And because it was designed for production,

00:03:57.039 --> 00:03:59.679
you can have the confidence to deploy it everywhere.

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:02.119
What do I mean by this?

00:04:02.119 --> 00:04:06.360
Well, in terms of foundation, it's built on NNG.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:09.119
This is short for Nano Message Next Generation.

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:12.320
This is a high-performance messaging library.

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:13.759
And because it's built on that,

00:04:13.759 --> 00:04:16.600
we have the optimal connection types built in.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.920
So things like inter-process communications,

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:21.480
TCP and TLS if you need it.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:27.480
We've also engineered base R serialization mechanism

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:31.600
to better support custom serialization

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:34.440
of newer cross-language data formats,

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.079
things like Arrow or Safe Tensors.

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:42.000
Because we have this foundation,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.880
Mirai scales to millions of tasks

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:47.160
over thousands of connections.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:50.519
And we can all do this at 1,000 times

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:52.559
the efficiency we could otherwise.

00:04:53.839 --> 00:04:56.640
The extra bit of engineering that we've done

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:59.640
are to create these zero-latency promises.

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:03.559
So if you use Mirai together with something like Shiny,

00:05:03.559 --> 00:05:06.559
you will notice the extra responsiveness from that.

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:09.920
And we come to this point,

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:13.239
which is why we have Parallel Pro in the first place.

00:05:13.239 --> 00:05:17.200
Mirai was designed to be used in production,

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:19.320
i.e. reliably.

00:05:19.359 --> 00:05:23.880
And it does this by adopting a very clear evaluation model

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:26.640
with a clean separation between

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:29.000
what's in your current environment

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.440
and what's in the environment of the process

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:35.760
which is actually doing the parallel work.

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:41.359
We've minimized the complexity of the package itself,

00:05:41.359 --> 00:05:44.359
and we've eliminated any hidden state.

00:05:45.239 --> 00:05:48.040
What this means for you is the code you write,

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:51.239
you can expect it to be evaluated transparently

00:05:51.239 --> 00:05:53.119
and reliably over time.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:57.040
And you can literally deploy this anywhere.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.720
So locally, on your own laptop,

00:06:00.679 --> 00:06:02.559
on a remote machine over SSH,

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:04.079
and this is what I'm gonna be covering

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:06.160
in the second half of the presentation,

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:07.720
or if you're lucky enough to have access

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:09.920
to a high-performance compute cluster,

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.519
you can use your scheduler of choice.

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:16.200
And then Mirai has this concept

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:18.839
of modular compute profiles.

00:06:18.839 --> 00:06:20.480
So you can actually be connected

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.679
to all three resource types at the same time.

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:28.880
And I'm gonna say one last thing about Mirai

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:32.320
before we move on to distributed computing,

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:35.559
and that we've not just put Mirai into Per,

00:06:35.559 --> 00:06:38.640
we've rolled Mirai out across our ecosystem.

00:06:39.519 --> 00:06:44.119
So Mirai is now the primary async backend for Shiny.

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:49.119
It is the only built-in async evaluator for Plumber 2.

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:53.679
And it's also an option to run things

00:06:53.679 --> 00:06:55.519
in parallel in tidy models,

00:06:55.519 --> 00:06:58.640
such as hyperparameter tuning.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:03.480
Now, Mirai is an RLib package,

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.920
so you can find extensive documentation

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:08.200
at mirai.rlib.org.

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:12.359
The next part of the presentation does contain some code,

00:07:12.359 --> 00:07:14.760
but the idea is not for you

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:17.359
to memorize the syntax in particular,

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:20.000
but it's just to show you intuitively

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.399
how Mirai works a bit under the hood,

00:07:22.399 --> 00:07:23.799
and to show you some patterns

00:07:23.799 --> 00:07:27.440
that you probably might not have come across yourself yet.

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:30.040
So just try and follow the code,

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:31.079
no need to memorize it,

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:32.720
there's extensive documentation.

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:38.079
So how might you use distributed Per?

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:42.279
And all I mean by distributed is,

00:07:42.279 --> 00:07:44.720
have your compute run on another machine,

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:47.820
so not on the laptop or the local machine you're using.

00:07:48.839 --> 00:07:50.440
Well, firstly, simply you can use it

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:51.679
to replace local compute.

00:07:51.679 --> 00:07:54.839
So maybe you're working on an underpowered laptop,

00:07:54.839 --> 00:07:58.079
and you actually need to do heavy computations,

00:07:58.079 --> 00:08:00.760
which are more suited to a workstation or a server.

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:05.440
Another way you can use distributed compute

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:07.119
is to extend your local compute.

00:08:07.119 --> 00:08:11.679
So as well as using all the calls on your laptop,

00:08:11.679 --> 00:08:14.959
you can also use another machine,

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:17.359
or even multiple machines on your network.

00:08:19.839 --> 00:08:21.160
And lastly, I'm gonna show you

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:22.720
how to use differentiated compute.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:26.200
So this is a case where you have a workflow

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:30.200
where certain calculations may require a GPU,

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:32.359
which you don't have on your local machine,

00:08:32.359 --> 00:08:33.520
but on another machine.

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:37.559
So before I do that,

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:40.200
for those of you who have not encountered

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:43.679
the new parallel functionality in Per yet,

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:47.000
what we've done is we've added this in parallel adverb.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:51.559
So whereas before you would map a function

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:53.880
over a list or a vector,

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:58.039
all you would do now is map in parallel

00:08:58.039 --> 00:08:59.799
a function over a list or a vector.

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:06.320
And again, before we move on to distributed case,

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:11.320
how would you run that parallel map

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:13.000
on your local computer,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.640
using all the calls available to you?

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:20.200
Well, as a user, you would call this function daemons

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:21.599
in the Mirai package.

00:09:23.239 --> 00:09:27.359
Daemons sets where and how

00:09:27.359 --> 00:09:29.679
you actually do this parallelization.

00:09:29.679 --> 00:09:31.739
And it's for the user to set this,

00:09:31.739 --> 00:09:34.859
because when you write the code,

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:39.820
your code may be in a package, for example,

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:42.099
and you don't know the resources

00:09:42.099 --> 00:09:43.460
that are available to the end user.

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:46.299
So when the user actually runs your code,

00:09:46.299 --> 00:09:48.460
they will call this daemons function.

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:50.859
And daemons sets where and how

00:09:50.859 --> 00:09:52.739
this parallelization actually happens.

00:09:54.659 --> 00:09:59.140
So in this case, to run things on your local laptop,

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:01.659
all you would do is you would pass a local URL

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:03.659
to daemons.

00:10:03.659 --> 00:10:06.539
What this does is this creates a socket

00:10:06.539 --> 00:10:09.239
which is listening for connections

00:10:09.239 --> 00:10:12.099
from other processes on your own machine.

00:10:12.099 --> 00:10:15.320
Think of this as setting up a base station.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:20.700
You would then call this function launch local.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:23.219
This actually spawns local processes,

00:10:23.219 --> 00:10:25.419
which dial in back to your local URL.

00:10:25.419 --> 00:10:27.059
So these are your subglides.

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:30.219
And this is how Mirai actually works under the hood.

00:10:31.659 --> 00:10:32.619
What you would actually do

00:10:32.619 --> 00:10:34.979
is you would actually just do this in one line

00:10:34.979 --> 00:10:38.340
and just say how many processes you want.

00:10:43.099 --> 00:10:44.299
So in the distributed case,

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:47.619
you're not just starting processes on your local machine.

00:10:47.619 --> 00:10:50.340
You're starting them on another machine.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:53.140
Now, SSH is the most ubiquitous way

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:55.440
to run things on other machines.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:56.780
So you would have come across this

00:10:56.780 --> 00:10:59.780
if you've ever set up a home network, for example.

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:03.659
Or conversely, if you spun up a cloud instance,

00:11:03.659 --> 00:11:06.900
something like an EC2 on AWS.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:08.900
The first thing you would get in that case

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:11.739
is the IP address of your cloud instance,

00:11:11.739 --> 00:11:13.099
and you would SSH in,

00:11:13.099 --> 00:11:15.539
and you would do all the setup for that instance.

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:18.580
Well, how would you use that in Mirai?

00:11:18.580 --> 00:11:21.219
Well, you would take that IP address,

00:11:21.219 --> 00:11:24.020
or if it's just a machine on your local network,

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:26.299
you can also use the host name,

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:29.919
and you would pass that to this SSH config function.

00:11:31.219 --> 00:11:34.700
What that does is that creates a remote launch configuration.

00:11:34.700 --> 00:11:36.400
This is a simple list.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:38.059
There's no other special source in that.

00:11:38.059 --> 00:11:40.820
So you can save that, you can reuse that,

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:43.780
you can even put this line in your .R profile.

00:11:45.739 --> 00:11:49.599
Next, we would call daemons like we did before,

00:11:49.599 --> 00:11:52.140
and in this case, we would use a host URL.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:56.979
The only difference here is that a host URL

00:11:56.979 --> 00:12:00.099
is available for connections from your network,

00:12:00.099 --> 00:12:01.940
so not just on your local machine.

00:12:03.099 --> 00:12:04.739
And then instead of launch local,

00:12:04.739 --> 00:12:06.739
we now say launch remote,

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:09.380
and we pass it the configuration that you've created.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:14.539
You can also do all of that on one line.

00:12:17.739 --> 00:12:20.299
And once you've done that,

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:26.260
the, sorry, when you launch those daemons,

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:28.780
you actually SSH into those machines

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:30.059
and create those processes,

00:12:30.059 --> 00:12:33.739
which dial back in to your host URL.

00:12:34.719 --> 00:12:37.700
So your host has to be able

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:39.739
to accept these incoming connections.

00:12:39.739 --> 00:12:41.460
Now, that might already be set up,

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:45.059
but if you're just using something like a local laptop,

00:12:45.059 --> 00:12:46.780
typically that won't be the case,

00:12:46.780 --> 00:12:48.099
because there'll be a firewall

00:12:48.099 --> 00:12:50.140
that's blocking all of these connections.

00:12:52.619 --> 00:12:54.739
What you would do in that case

00:12:54.739 --> 00:12:58.159
is use SSH tunneling to get around this problem.

00:12:59.659 --> 00:13:02.380
Now, I'm gonna explain SSH tunneling

00:13:02.380 --> 00:13:04.219
in the simplest way possible,

00:13:04.219 --> 00:13:06.260
without the use of a diagram.

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:09.359
So, whereas before, you have a remote machine

00:13:09.359 --> 00:13:12.219
connecting back into your local machine,

00:13:12.219 --> 00:13:13.820
all that's happening now is,

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:16.780
on both ends, connections are local to local,

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:17.820
so think of it as a loop,

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:19.340
local to local,

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:23.099
and you only have the SSH connection acting as a bridge.

00:13:24.659 --> 00:13:25.500
Okay.

00:13:26.580 --> 00:13:28.739
What does that mean in terms of,

00:13:28.739 --> 00:13:31.700
for Mirai, well, all we have to do

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:33.659
is add tunnel equals true

00:13:33.659 --> 00:13:35.099
when you're creating the configuration.

00:13:35.099 --> 00:13:37.140
That's the only change you need.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:39.020
But when you get to set up daemons,

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:42.380
instead of host URL, you're moving back to local URL,

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:45.539
because all connections are actually local now.

00:13:45.539 --> 00:13:47.820
But you have to remember to set TCP equals true,

00:13:47.859 --> 00:13:50.419
because SSH requires TCP connections.

00:13:51.419 --> 00:13:55.299
And we launch remote the same as before.

00:13:57.140 --> 00:13:58.340
And you can do it in one line,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:13:59.419
and once you've done that,

00:13:59.419 --> 00:14:03.059
you will have six daemons on a remote machine,

00:14:03.059 --> 00:14:06.380
regardless of the firewall settings that you have.

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:13.260
So, the second way you can use distributed compute

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:15.700
is to extend your local compute.

00:14:15.700 --> 00:14:19.340
So you can use both cores on your local machine

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:22.179
and remote daemons on another machine at the same time.

00:14:22.179 --> 00:14:25.520
Or this could be daemons on many machines.

00:14:27.299 --> 00:14:29.099
Example of doing this,

00:14:29.099 --> 00:14:30.979
you create your remote configuration,

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:34.739
you set daemons with a host URL.

00:14:34.739 --> 00:14:37.140
This is available to other computers,

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:40.260
but also to processes on your own machine.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:43.059
So you can launch daemons remotely,

00:14:43.059 --> 00:14:45.140
and you can launch daemons locally.

00:14:45.979 --> 00:14:48.580
And you will have 12 daemons

00:14:48.580 --> 00:14:50.380
for you to spread your work over.

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:56.020
Lastly, I'm gonna show you

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:58.179
how to do differentiated compute.

00:14:58.179 --> 00:14:59.700
So this is where parts of your code

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:01.580
need to be run on a GPU,

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:03.179
which you may not have on your laptop,

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:04.340
but on another machine.

00:15:06.659 --> 00:15:08.580
To do this, you would make use of

00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:11.140
Mirai's concept of compute profiles.

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:13.260
These are different daemon settings

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:15.260
which can coexist at the same time.

00:15:16.179 --> 00:15:19.059
So in this example, if I call daemon six,

00:15:19.059 --> 00:15:21.500
that uses the default compute profile.

00:15:22.659 --> 00:15:25.340
I can also set up remote daemons

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:28.900
and pass a name to this .compute argument.

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:31.260
This creates a compute profile called GPU.

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:34.179
And how I would use this,

00:15:35.460 --> 00:15:37.260
if I do a parallel map,

00:15:38.219 --> 00:15:40.979
that will use the default compute profile,

00:15:41.820 --> 00:15:43.460
which in this case will run locally.

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:48.140
Anything I wrap in with daemons,

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:51.619
and here I give it the name of the compute profile GPU,

00:15:53.059 --> 00:15:55.780
anything within that scope will run

00:15:57.580 --> 00:15:59.140
with that compute profile.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:01.419
So in this case, remotely.

00:16:02.859 --> 00:16:06.340
And that's all I've got to share with you.

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:09.900
I've shown you how to do distributed computing

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:12.659
to replace local compute, extend local compute,

00:16:12.659 --> 00:16:14.580
and to do differentiated compute.

00:16:16.419 --> 00:16:18.440
Thank you very much, I'm open for questions.

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:21.440
Okay, we do have time for questions.

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:34.559
I use one, some package versioning

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:37.559
can vary in a remote parallel plan.

00:16:37.559 --> 00:16:39.239
Is it the responsibility of the developer

00:16:39.239 --> 00:16:40.960
to ensure versions are compatible

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:42.640
or does the first-class MRI attempt

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:47.359
to implement constraints on similar environments?

00:16:47.359 --> 00:16:51.280
So MRI has a very explicit evaluation model,

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:54.119
doesn't do anything that's implicit under the hood,

00:16:54.119 --> 00:16:59.119
it doesn't try to second-guess what you have in your code.

00:16:59.559 --> 00:17:01.200
So it's your responsibility to have

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:03.599
the same package versions on your own computer

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:06.680
and any other remote computer

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:09.380
that you want to run MRI daemons on.

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:11.219
Thank you.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:15.939
Does MRI's visual tasks need an underlying event loop

00:17:15.939 --> 00:17:18.859
for those outputs of a later patch?

00:17:19.939 --> 00:17:24.140
So the event-driven promises uses the later event loop

00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:27.040
and it uses it in a very efficient way.

00:17:29.199 --> 00:17:31.619
The model for MRI is,

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:37.180
it uses a thread pool,

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:39.420
so it's not limited

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:44.680
to just the R event loop,

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:48.439
but it uses later basically to call into the R event loop

00:17:48.439 --> 00:17:50.900
when needed for things like promises

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:54.219
and in applications like Shiny and Plummer.

00:17:56.459 --> 00:17:59.880
Are there any tips for deciding how many?

00:18:01.459 --> 00:18:06.160
Right, so MRI consciously doesn't automatically detect

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:07.800
or attempt to set the number of workers,

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.839
this is always the responsibility of the user.

00:18:10.839 --> 00:18:12.339
The reason for this is,

00:18:13.719 --> 00:18:17.400
it's fairly simple to know how many cores your laptop has,

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:20.680
so most of the time it's not that useful

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:22.300
to do automatic detection,

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:24.920
but also the software can never know

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:27.560
what else is going on in your machine at the same time.

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:29.079
So you might be running something else,

00:18:29.079 --> 00:18:31.319
it may not even be in R.

00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:33.199
And this becomes especially important

00:18:33.199 --> 00:18:35.160
if you're actually on a shared resource,

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:37.199
so not just on your local laptop,

00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:40.280
but for example, on a high-performance compute cluster,

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:42.319
you have to share the resources with others,

00:18:42.319 --> 00:18:47.319
so you need to explicitly specify what are those resources.

00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:51.359
I will finish my talk.

00:18:51.359 --> 00:18:52.180
Thank you.

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:53.020
Thank you.

